    <blockquote>
      <title>
        <ulink url="http://www.h-online.com/open/features/The-history-of-Linux-1331088.html"
          >h-online/Dr. Oliver Diedrich: The history of Linux</ulink>
      </title>
      <para><emphasis role="bold">When Linus Torvalds released Linux 0.01 on the internet 20 years ago, his idea of a free Unix clone to which anyone could contribute touched a creativenerve in people. Today, it would be impossible to imagine an IT world without Linux.</emphasis></para>
      <para>It has been twenty years since Linus Torvalds programmed the first few lines of what
        would become the Linux kernel. An IT student at the time, Torvalds wasn&apos;t yet thinking of an
        operating system, he just wanted to explore the capabilities of his PC&apos;s 386 processor.
        Eventually, his memory management, process switching and I/O experiments developed into
        something that resembled a rudimentary operating system kernel. (...)</para>
    </blockquote>
    <blockquote>
      <title>
        <ulink url="http://arstechnica.com/open-source/news/2011/08/march-of-the-penguin-ars-looks-back-at-20-years-of-linux.ars">arstechnica/Ryan Paul: March of the Penguin: Ars looks back at 20 years of Linux</ulink>
